2025-12-12 | Text Editor with Undo and Redo Operations

	Question
Implement the following functions for the text editor:
1.	void append(char x)
2.	void undo()
3.	void redo()
4.	string read()

	Approach
1.	Use two stacks:
	-	mainText → stores the current characters of the document.
	-	redoStack → stores characters removed by undo.
2.	append(x):
	-	Push x into mainText.
	-	Clear redoStack because a new operation invalidates redo history.
3.	undo():
	-	If mainText is not empty:
		-	Pop the top character from mainText.
		-	Push it into redoStack.
4.	redo():
	-	If redoStack is not empty:
		-	Pop the top character from redoStack.
		-	Push it back into mainText.
5.	read():
	-	Convert the contents of mainText into a string (from bottom to top).
6.	Time Complexity:
	-	append, undo, redo → O(1)
	-	read → O(n)
7.	Space Complexity:
	-	O(n), where n is the number of characters appended.

	Solution

class TextEditor {
    stack<char> mainText;
    stack<char> redoStack;

public:
    void append(char x) {
        mainText.push(x);
        // New append invalidates redo history
        while (!redoStack.empty())
            redoStack.pop();
    }

    void undo() {
        if (!mainText.empty()) {
            redoStack.push(mainText.top());
            mainText.pop();
        }
    }

    void redo() {
        if (!redoStack.empty()) {
            mainText.push(redoStack.top());
            redoStack.pop();
        }
    }

    string read() {
        string result;
        stack<char> temp = mainText;

        while (!temp.empty()) {
            result.push_back(temp.top());
            temp.pop();
        }

        reverse(result.begin(), result.end());
        return result;
    }
};
